FriendsFest: the comedy series that taught us important lessons about men's friendship
The absence of similar characters in the series is evident, given that the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, suicide rates among young men reaching the peak of the last 15 years.
In 2013, suicide was the main cause of deaths in men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more frequent in men than in women.
In an attempt to address the problem, the Campaign against Unfortunate Life (Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM)) designated 2015 as the Year of Man, wanting to question the culture that prevents men from asking for help when they need it.
Friendship lies at the centre of the struggle towards the success of this challenge.
A recent study conducted by more than 2000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends “with a healthy condition”, his chances of recovery are doubled.
To the same extent, for people who are not depressed, a circle of healthy mental friends reduces to half the likelihood of mental disorders.
Of course, for friendship to have effect, it must first be accessible.
In this era of communication dominated by social networks, where emphasis is placed on the style and not on the substance, the immediate nature of the response has often priority before the contact with meaning.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even though in reality isolation is the dominant one.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values - our inner desire for personal development and friendship - which also affect our mental health.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money does not even buy happiness.
The beauty of the Friends series was that it focused on this idea.
The characters were not defined by the job but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The mood of Joey's and Chandler's frequent hugs, the moments when they look at football in the comfortable folleries and Ross' passion for Rachel came from the fact that men can be associated with this situation, even though they often want to explore their feelings completely.
As a social worker explained to me: ..."My role in listening to people with suicidal and depressed tendencies has shown how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference."
Often, people who call us do not feel able to talk to their friends.
The old saying to deal with yourself is strong, as is the feeling of being perceived as a weak person if you talk about problems open.
Friends is one of the series that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term psychological adaptation mechanisms.
The series highlighted the little moments of friendship between men.
As much as it helps the objective, external intervention, through the phone, people gathered in moments of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
Thus, if you are participating at this weekend at FriendsFest organized by Comedy Central, with the complete editing of the filming plates to celebrate the event, why not invite your friends to a coffee in Central Perk.
Or, and better, if you see someone alone in Starbucks, smile and greet.
You never know what difference your friendship might make.
