The government approved, on Wednesday, "National Immigration Strategy for the period 2015-2018" and "The Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "a stage at which Romania goes in the efforts to modernize the immigration management process on the national territory", according to a press release.
The source mentioned shows that the strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and action guidelines that reflect the policies set at European level, adapted to national realities.
Given the problems faced by the countries in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures were taken to manage the unitary and coherent situations resulting from the possible influx of illegal immigrants into the territory of Romania, generated by situations of a crisis of political, social, economic or military nature.
"Roman authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time they will give special attention to citizens from states with potential migrationist or that can affect national security," adds the remembered source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in the border areas of Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets out a few general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, stricter controls of the legality of the headquarters of third-country nationals in the territory of Romania and the corresponding application of the removal and restrictive measures, the improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the implementation and implementation of the overall strategic objectives.
Among these are: facilitating access to Romania's territory of third-party citizens who respond to the demands for the occupation of the labour force, promoting access of third-country nationals to Romanian higher educational institutions for areas and professions identified as deficits.
With reference to the Action Plan for 2015, the Government appreciates that it represents "a means of establishing concrete activities leading to the creation of a flexible system for halting the growing migration phenomenon".
